(43, 19, 31, 6, 8, 29, 29, 'that the bodies should not remain', 'Hanging Bodies and Burial Customs', 'Both passages emphasize the urgency of removing bodies from trees or crosses before the onset of a sacred day. This connection highlights the cultural practice of ensuring that no bodies remain exposed during significant religious observances.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 31, 2, 12, 16, 16, 'that the bodies should not remain upon the cross on the sabbath day', 'Sabbath Observance and Preparation', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of preparation for the Sabbath. John 19:31 notes the urgency to remove bodies before the Sabbath, while Exodus 12:16 outlines the holy convocation and restrictions on work during the Sabbath.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 31, 3, 23, 7, 16, 'sabbath day was an high day', 'Sabbath Observance Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of the Sabbath, with John 19:31 noting the urgency to remove bodies before the Sabbath, while Leviticus 23:7-16 outlines the holy nature of the Sabbath and related offerings. This connection highlights the importance of observing the Sabbath in both contexts.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 31, 5, 21, 22, 23, NULL, 'Connection of Burial Practices', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of not leaving a body hanging overnight. John 19:31 reflects the urgency to remove the bodies before the Sabbath, paralleling Deuteronomy 21:22-23''s command to bury the body the same day.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 32, 43, 19, 18, 18, NULL, 'Crucifixion Context Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of Jesus and two others during the crucifixion. The mention of ''two other'' in both verses highlights their simultaneous execution alongside Jesus.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 32, 42, 23, 39, 43, NULL, 'Crucifixion and Condemnation Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of condemnation during crucifixion. In John, the soldiers break the legs of the condemned, while in Luke, the malefactors acknowledge their own guilt and the innocence of Jesus.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 34, 62, 5, 6, 6, 'blood and water', 'Connection of Water and Blood', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of ''water'' and ''blood'' in relation to Jesus Christ. The SOURCE verse describes the physical manifestation of blood and water from Jesus'' side, while the TARGET passage highlights their theological importance in affirming His identity.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 34, 38, 12, 10, 10, 'pierced his side', 'Connection of Piercing Imagery', 'This connection highlights the theme of piercing in both passages. John 19:34 describes Jesus being pierced, while Zechariah 12:10 speaks of looking upon ''him whom they have pierced.''', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 34, 38, 13, 1, 1, 'blood and water', 'Connection of Blood and Water', 'This connection highlights the imagery of cleansing associated with blood and water. Both passages emphasize the theme of purification, with Zechariah referencing a fountain for sin and uncleanness, paralleling the blood and water that flowed from Jesus'' side.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 34, 26, 36, 25, 25, NULL, 'Cleansing Through Water Imagery', 'This connection highlights the imagery of water as a means of cleansing. In John 19:34, the blood and water that flow from Jesus'' side can be seen as a fulfillment of the cleansing promise in Ezekiel 36:25, where water is used to purify from filthiness.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
